2 notary public or to at least one of the two witnesses before whom the act is
3 acknowledged.
4 (b) The notary public is physically located in a parish in which he is
5 authorized to exercise notarial functions at the time of the acknowledgment and
6 is in possession of the original instrument bearing the signature of the party
7 making the acknowledgment.
8 (2) An acknowledgment made pursuant to this Subsection shall be valid
9 only if all of the following apply:
10 (a) The act, transaction, or instrument is not required by law to be
11 executed as an authentic act.
12 (b) The party making the acknowledgment declares to the notary public
13 and two witnesses, while all are participating in a simultaneous audiovisual
14 transmission, that the signature on the instrument is his signature and that he
15 executed the instrument as his own free act and deed.
16 (c) The notary public states in the acknowledgment that the party was
17 either personally known to the notary public or if identified by at least one of
18 the witnesses thereto who personally knew the party, the name of the witness.
19 (d) The acknowledgment states that it was made pursuant to a
20 declaration made by a party to the original instrument in simultaneous
21 audiovisual transmission in the presence of the notary public and two witnesses.
22 D.E. This Chapter supplements and does not repeal, supersede, or limit the
23 provisions of the Louisiana Uniform Electronic Transactions Act, R.S. 9:2601 et seq.
